<paragraph blockId="7.[412,1808,2328,2523]" lastBlockId="8.[319,1717,335,579]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="113" pageId="7" pageNumber="112">
This genus may be separated from other genera of the tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muir" authorityYear="1917" box="[1574,1751,2430,2471]" class="Insecta" family="Derbidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="112" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Otiocerini">Otiocerini</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: media separated from the stem of subcosta-radius; head when viewed laterally broadly rounded, following the contour of the compound eyes; antennae short, without a subantennal process. Nine species are known in this genus. They seem to be rather widely distributed in the East Indian and Pacific islands. Muir has described a species from 
<collectingCountry box="[424,609,539,579]" name="Malawi" pageId="8" pageNumber="113">Nyasaland</collectingCountry>
which is the only species known outside the Pacific area.
</paragraph>
